< Text>
Della Curva and Lisa and Bert are truly amazing! I grew up in southern California and now live in Alabama. I was traveling home for Christmas and knew I needed to go visit this plus size dress store as there is nothing like it near me. It was my first time trying on wedding dresses and I found the one! My mom and I  had the whole store to ourselves  to pick out and try on any dress that I wanted and I felt so confident knowing that all the dresses in the store would fit me. They had a large selection of every style imaginable. The prices were extremely reasonable as were shipping charges back to Alabama. I cannot thank them enough for how amazing this experience was and it will be a fond memory me and my mom can look back on. I cannot wait to wear my beautiful wedding dress back in sweet home Alabama!</Text>

< review>
Our appointment was booked on a Sunday, when this beautiful bridal store is typically closed. Boutique is a little hard to find, on the 2nd floor but there is metered street and parking lot spaces.

Not only was our appointment confirmed by text the day prior, we instantly felt welcomed as soon as we walked into the gorgeous store that is Della Curva. Alexa was waiting for us with her grace and patience. Our group felt totally taken care of and we felt no pressure and the space was so comfortable with plenty of seating for our 6 person group. Alexa listened as we spoke about what our bride wanted and she went in our direction and had great comments for us too.

Our appointment was probably really long but we really appreciated that we got to take the time to try a bunch of different styles for the bride. NOW let's get to the dresses.... they were all so beautiful, seriously what a great selection and finally a plus sized store that carries actual pretty wedding dresses, we had previously gone to David's Bridal and we would describe that experience as a frozen meal that has already expired, compared to Della Curva that was a hot, well executed steak or vegetarian dish, basically there was a dress that would work for any bride! Also, the prices were so reasonable, truly getting a value with these dresses, but seriously Alexa was amazing and we can't wait to make our final order!

Thank you again, 10/10 recommend Della Curva, if you come here, you will think about getting divorced JUST to go shopping here again for another beautiful dress.< /review>

<Text>Came here to get my first full setup of gear after borrowing and only playing once or twice a year for ~6 years.

The guys who work here were extremely nice and easy to work with. They didn't guide me too much but were there to answer questions I had and were ready to answer those questions in depth.

I've had an order take a while do to lost forms, but this is an isolated incident and they didn't charge labor. Overall a good store, but lacking a bit in part selection and number of staff.</Review>

Based on my requirements, he pointed me to gas blow-back versions of my weapons, which provide the recoil (albeit minimized) and realistic round count that I'm used to. I've already talked a friend of mine into trying out airsoft with me because of my experience at Airsoft Extreme San Diego with Lawrence.  I will definitely be making my purchase from AEX.<//Text>

<name>Katrina Avila</name><time>1474224286583</time>< Review>
Whenever I come, I am asked 3-5 times by the staff if I need help finding something. Each time I say no, and I've noticed them watch me as I browse around the store. Whenever I am holding a bottle of vitamins they will try to hold it up front for me, and I say no thank you. I'm not sure if the staff is just overly helpful or if they assume that I am stealing. Either way, it's a bit annoying. I've come many times over the last couple months and each visit is the same. There is one staff member that isn't so overbearing like the other two, but I mostly encounter the other 2. A couple times I decided not to make a purchase and go to Vitamin World instead, because I was a bit insulted.<//Review>

<userid>102127821011132310638</userid><username>Ankit Patel< /username>< Review>
Since 1956, The Bakersfield Museum of Art has been showcasing fine art and is said to be one of the city‚Äôs top attractions.

Inside this large museum are two large galleries and two smaller ones. The permanent collection features art by local artists. The rest of the rotating exhibits feature a mix of art from all over.

The outside grounds of the museum are home to some beautiful gardens and sculptures.</Review>

I love this place but was disappointed the Rain Forest exhibit was closed. My favorite part was simulated flying like a pterosaur - the new name for pterodactyls. Lots of fun. EDIT: I got a call from the district manager, Steve about the mishap and he tried what he could (within his limits) to restore faith in the store. Unfortunately we couldn't come to a reasonable agreement. I still am disappointed with my original experience, but I'm amending my review of the store - in part because I believe that Steve is telling me the truth and would have been able to do a lot more if it wasn't for the time passing (and he just sounds like a nice guy), and in part because in reality, I should have been more persistent at the time to make the correction - which is not actually a huge deal. The phone itself is great - no issues there, just not a dual sim... and whatever, I still like the product. I would still return to this store, I think I would just double check the information I'm given before walking out the door. Was it just a miscommunication? I don't know, but I'm willing to give the salesperson the benefit of the doubt and not blame the store itself for what might have been the mistake of one employee.

ORIGINAL POST: I called the store to see if they had the Note10+ dual sim, they said that they did, then the sales person said that it was the last one that they had, sold it to me, helped me get it activated (minus the dual sim) and then told me that I needed to have Verizon help me set up the dual sim. I wasn't able to get in touch with Verizon until the 14th day after purchase and then found out that I was sold the wrong phone. I spoke with the sales person and she said that I could no longer return the phone. My own fault since I didn't check the model number on the phone until it was too late. Just pretty disappointed that I was lied to in order for them to make a sale.< /text>

<name>Millennium Productions<//name><Date>1484184865417<//Date><Rate>1< /Rate>< Review>
GoWireless has a C- rating with the BBB??!!!

I cannot begin to describe how disgusted I am with GoWireless as a company, their N.P. store manager Matt, as well as Verizon to a lesser degree, and I will describe our experience in great detail. Similar to what Patrick W here experienced, my Mother and 16yr old Daughter were not only completely and utterly defrauded at this store by a salesman who not only used profanity to describe some of the HTC 1 phones negatively, but when I was made aware of the fraud, went in personally to handle it with the manager Matt, his lack of any actions or promised follow through made it clear that this is how they do business and is indicative of GoWireless as a company.
This all started back in August, when my daughter broke her HTC 1, and went into our local GoWireless store here on Broadbeck Dr., in the Islands shopping center. My Mom took her, since they share a plan together. The salesman they dealt with was aggressive and pushy, and put a bad taste in my daughters mouth. She wanted another HTC 1, as she was already familiar with it, and does very little beyond using it for calls and texting, but the salesman told her that she didn't want that phone, it was, Quote, "A Piece of S#I!" and that she should only get the top of the line HTC model, the HTC 10. He told them that they were eligible for a "Free Upgrade", and conveniently left out that the the full price of the phone would be amortized on her bill. My Mother, being on a fixed income, would certainly not have agreed to the $700+ phone, no how/no way.
Once I was made aware of her now nearly $200 bill, 2 months later after she was complaining of the second bill in a row that was now doubled, I called Verizon to find out what was going on. The Verizon rep explained that this new HTC 10 phone had had been added to the account, as well as insurance on both phones, (My Mother's phone is 4 years old and doesn't need a $15 per month plan!). The Verizon rep also expressed disdain over the situation, and was very apologetic on behalf of Verizon, indicating that these types of situations were anything but uncommon. She said that these Verizon affiliates are well known for these types of tactics, and unfortunately, there was nothing she could do, this would have to be taken up with GoWireless directly.
I called this local GoWireless to find out who the manager was, and after a week, was finally able coordinate time off from work to go in and talk directly with the Manager, Matt. I wanted to give him the opportunity to rectify this issue, and so my Mother and I explained the situation. Matt indicated that he knew who the salesman was, and also alluded to acknowledging that this was anything but the first time there have been issues with that employee. Unfortunately, that salesman no longer works at that location. Matt expressed what appeared to be genuine concern, and promised that he would call me back with an update regarding what could be done on Monday, or Tuesday at the latest. Monday came and went, Tuesday also, then Wed/Thurs/Friday...... no reply. I called Saturday and talked to Matt. It took him a bit to remember who I was/what the situation was, and then just indicated that he had not heard back from anyone at corporate-no mention of why he had not bothered to follow up with a reply earlier to me as promised to indicate this. At this point, his demeanor was one of indifference, and I was done with wasting anymore valuable time waiting for him to do nothing. I asked for his superior's number, and indicated I would take it from here.
I will be contacting Verizon, HTC, the BBB, as well as local media sources, I already have all the contacts from my TV/Motion Picture Product Placement company. The CV here is a realistically small/tight knit community, word gets around quick. It's unfortunate that I do not have positive feedback for GoWireless.<//Review>

< Review>
I had visited Sam Maloof before the whole complex of buildings was moved from where the 210 freeway cuts through. He had said at that time every stick and rock had to be moved by Cal Trans because the 210 was cutting through it. So here we are many years later.

The visit today was free except for the house tour which was $5 but it ended at 3.00 pm and I missed it. Anyway the garden, gallery and gift shop was very pleasant and they had a lot of sculptures on display in the garden for today only. There many events occurring throughout the year so check back on their web site and plan your trip accordingly.<//Review>

< text>
I had visited Sam Maloof before the whole complex of buildings was moved from where the 210 freeway cuts through. He had said at that time every stick and rock had to be moved by Cal Trans because the 210 was cutting through it. So here we are many years later.

The visit today was free except for the house tour which was $5 but it ended at 3.00 pm and I missed it. Anyway the garden, gallery and gift shop was very pleasant and they had a lot of sculptures on display in the garden for today only. There many events occurring throughout the year so check back on their web site and plan your trip accordingly.</text>

< Review>
I take my baby (under 1) to Camarena Oakhurst &I go to Camarena Coarsegold.

I'm disappointed in the reviews on here... it's the medical field, not a fine dining experience. Every case is unique in its own way... seriously &y'all wonder why doctors don't want to work in our mountain community. Anyway.... personal experiences:

The new pediatrician in Oakhurst is amazing. She has a warm heart, an open ear, and non-judgemental persona. She's on top of it when it comes to knowledge, and makes herself available outside of appointments, if need be. I'm so glad to have her here. I've only had to "wait" when I've called in same day or prior day &it wasn't even that long.

The doctor in Coarsegold is very patient.  She has personality &knowledge; I like that. The office staff seems to be a mixed of new &seasoned (I also appreciate that because we need more medical field personnel around here!) They are pleasant to be around &again the wait time is to be as expected: some days are longer than others-- maybe the people complaining about wait time should remember that when they are asked to explain why they are there. ü§£

Anywho. Camarena is a blessing to our community. Big shout out to both places. Thank you, thank you, thank you. My family appreciates you.<//Review>

<Text>This is a new restaurant that opened few weeks back. The food was one of the best. We ordered Thai Garden Salad with House Made Peanut Dressing, Green Curry with White Rice and Drunken Noodles. They are very knowledgeable about food preferences for vegetarians. As a vegetarian, they made sure that the dishes we ordered were without animal products such as oyster or fish sauce. The wait staff (Peach and her sister) are excellent and very welcoming of customers coming and trying there new restaurant. <user_name>Aditya Joshi<//user_name></record></dataset><record>
< text>
Came here last weekend on a Sunday for our schedule visit at 2:30pm. My boyfriend and I booked our tickets two weeks in advance for $24 each per adult and $10 for parking. Recommend to book ahead of time for your time slot, which allows you up to 30 minutes to enter, meaning from 2:30-3pm is our entry time. The lines were short and ample parking for visitors. Most animals were out and about but the reptiles and bugs building was closed and play structures are closed off from kids due to covid protocols. There‚Äôs a free gondola to take to see more animals at the top and the lines went by fast. Reason why gave one star less is because of the cleaning and sanitizing they are doing at the zoo. I felt that the way the gondolas were being sanitized could be better. They are sanitizing by just a quick spray of disinfectant into the gondola vs spraying the seats and wiping down spots that may be touched. People are getting hand sanitized before they enter but I also saw a few families slip by without doing so. I personally would feel more safe with them being more strict on their workers to follow and clean when not everyone has had their chance at receiving the vaccine yet. However, this zoo is worth checking out if you haven‚Äôt before. Not a whole lot of animals to see compared to other zoos but the gondola seems like an attraction to many that‚Äôs different from other Bay Area zoos.</text>
<response>{'time': 1618341963102, 'text': 'Thank you Amanda for the feedback on Gondola safety and out sanitizing protocols. We have forwarded this to the Operations Department so they can also see your feedback. We are happy you enjoyed your Zoo visit'}< /response>< name>
Amanda Cheung</name>

<user_name>Sacra 916< /user_name><Date>1619617771988< /Date>< rate>
4<//rate>
< review>
Fun zoo for all! Perfect for kids. The zoo itself is located up in the Oakland Hills, giving it a very unique backdrop. If you have a membership to another zoo, you can get discounted tickets at 50% off and free parking (parking normally $10). Check to see if your zoo is listed on the "Reciprocal list" to qualify for this discount, although the only way to purchase these discounted tickets is in person. The zoo hasn't built this into their online reservation system. For all others, if visiting during COVID, you'll need to reserve tickets online. Many cool animals, a freaking gondola ride üòÉ and probably the best zoo food options I've seen. The food although expensive, was fresh and tasty. They serve beer!! Zoo is the perfect size, not too big, not too small. I think they also have a carousel and train ride, which were closed because of COVID. The gondola ride was a highlight and comes with the price of admission. You could ride it as many times as you want and the views are awesome. Food court and more animals are located at the top of the gondola ride<//review>

< text>
I haven't been to this zoo in many years and I was shocked to see how awesome and beautiful it has become. The new gondola and upper area of the Zoo was an amazing update. The animals have so much space to roam around and the overlook of the cities makes you feel like you are on top of the world. The online ticket purchase was super easy and the crowd was definitely perfect for a Wednesday afternoon. I'm sure it sells out on the weekend. Definitely wear good comfy walking shoes as the hilly terrain is rough for some. I definitely forgot how hilly this place was. Lol. But it's not a huge place so it doesnt feel overwhelming and like you have to rush to see it all. Its perfect!</text>

<user_id>101302542680492584418<//user_id>< review>
Great time! Awesome to walk around. Food available. Try to get an early RSVP, 2 weeks in advance for weekends. Weekday's schedule are usually open depending on the day. Don't just drive there, pay for everything online including parking pass. Make sure to at least have the ticket barcodes from email pdf available on phone to enter park. Had a blast! Snack shop has hot food & drinks but hot food don't last all day; they ran out by 3pm. But everything else was great! We got food, walked around with mask on, and of course 6 ft social distancing. Employees will create lines if too many people are wanting to view the same animal to prevent overcrowding 1 area. Staff was excellent!</review>

<user_id>111064400436870338606< /user_id>< name>
D Nguyen< /name>
< time>
1606779465024<//time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Our family really enjoyed the Glowrati event! There was just the right amount of people. The flow of the lines and the atmosphere was relaxing. Food & concessions were open for purchase, however we brought our own snacks. The weather was amazing and not that chilly the evening of 11/28. You can enter within an hour of your reservation time on your tickets and you can stay as long as you want until closing at 10 pm. The earlier, the better I think. Parking was easy because of it and we got the first space in front of the entrance, which never happens. Everybody was wearing masks even though we were outside. The gondola ride up the hill was open and you can fit a double back-to-back stroller inside, not sure about the tandem. Super convenient because we didn't have to take the kids out. We have the Contour. It was a great little family outing for the Thanksgiving weekend. There were bubbles and a big floor piano for the kiddos to stomp on along with music, however for those who are strict about the social distancing among kids, probably best to divert to a different location.<//Review>

< Review>
What a wonderful place to visit with family/kids. Well, any animal lover will enjoy it greatly. Big number of animals to see, learn about their habitat and discover something new. Making reservations online was easy. Staff on site is very helpful. Everything is clean, COVID- safe, everyone is masked and distancing. Stroller friendly.
Some areas are closed but that‚Äôs perfectly understandable. Gondola was a lot of fun. Separate are with California native animals was a blast to see. We hope to come back soon!<//Review>

A nice zoo for kids and the family. Right now you book a time/date in advance and the spots do fill up so you'll want to plan ahead. We went in the afternoon and many animals were active. There were lots of staff on site to answer questions and keep things moving. Most people respected wearing a mask and social distancing. There were some spots that got a bit crowded but you could always find space.</text>

The gondola made this zoo experience stand out from others. There are a good variety of animals; this zoo and the neighboring San Francisco zoo each have animals that are not available in the other, so it makes both zoos worthwhile to visit. <Review>We spent about four hours there, and not everything is available during this pandemic. Thankfully I bought membership and can take my family back once the other area's are open. Staff was helpful and sanitary. The gondola was amazing, the bears and monkeys put on a good show just playing around. And there is plenty for small children to enjoy. The gift shop was disappointing with a very small selection that caters to small children.</Review>< pictures>

Tammy Reynolds</username>
<Time>1619068767038< /Time><rate>5<//rate>< Review>
I am 51 years old and can honestly say this trip to the zoo was my favorite. The animals were so Interactive it's insane. I watched a baboon put a blanket on its head about five times to make me laugh then the last time he did it I asked my boyfriend if he thought he could see where he was going and no sooner did I do that did the monkey run right into a pole. He sat down took the blanket off his head and shook his head like it knocked the wind out of him. I about died. Everything was amazing at the Zoo today and what's all going on in the world it was greatly appreciated. A must-see Zoo if you're ever in the Oakland area or surrounding area.< /Review>

< Review>
The zoo inside is good for families. Some animals, like tiger and jaguar are always sleeping. Bears are always fighting with each other. Not many people are visiting the zoo in the covid19 situation. But the only concern from us is that the zoo is located in Oakland, which is not a safe place for families to drive through.</Review>

<user_id>105858627583928969574<//user_id><username>Mama Fox</username>< date>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
Visited in Aug 2020 a few weeks after reopening. Purchased timed-entry tickets and parking online ahead of our visit, as currently required. Went with a senior, who appreciated the many benches for resting on. Pleasant employees. Employees and visitors followed the mask requirement. This was our first visit using the gondola to the California Trail loop. Beautiful addition to the zoo! Great to see local animals as well as ones from around the world. Some of the "welcome back" messages on whiteboards throughout the park named individual animals; I would love to have that information posted more permanently for the larger/older/easy to identify animals. Some areas of the zoo are currently closed (amusement park, petting zoo), so check the website if you have a particular destination in mind.< /text>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
Although several areas were still closed where social distancing is not possible, we were still able to enjoy nearly all of the zoo. Staff were plentiful, friendly, and knowledgeable. Habitats looked so nice I could live there. And the burger and fries at the cafe were awesome. The hills can be a bit steep for mobility challenged patrons, but there are plenty of benches and lots of shade to rest a bit. The animals looked happy and healthy with many enrichment activities and areas for them.<//Text>

< text>
Great place to visit...Best for kids..All day fun..The visiting fee was 24 dollars per person..So many species of animals are there.. Their is a show where at the end of the show u can touch animals which was fun.. I touched Python...Food is good.. Their are three adventure rides one is gondola ride which will be free if you buy admission tickets of 24 dollars.. second one is another trip which is of 6 dollars which is little boring good for kids and the third one is on train where u have to buy 2 tickets per person in this trip we will see Australian species..It is full on fun... Restrooms are available..We have to stand in queues for all the adventure trips.. The zoo will closes at 5...< /text>

<Text>We had a great time. It was great for our older kids but for our preschool age kids not so much. All the play areas and  petting zoo were all closed.  Water fountains all turned off and only the stores open at the entrance. Bring your own beverages or buy it when you first get there because all the usual eating spots are closed. Everything else was closed. Was not worth the entrance fee when everything for the kids is off limits. The time limit also has you feeling rushed. Gives you barely enough time to get around the whole zoo. With little ones it a little harder. The ride up the mountain was amazing. We all enjoyed it and loved all the animals up there. Again, wish the play areas were open and water fountains. But with Covid it all has to be closed. I just don‚Äôt think it was worth the $120 we paid to get in when all the kids stuff were closed off. <name>Karen V Chin</name><Time>1563242222361</Time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Text>
Wonderful place for the whole family to go explore, learn, and have fun together. There is the zoo, the panoramic gondola üö† ride in which you can see the Bay Area (strollers and wheel chair friendly), and Adventure Landing (Kiddy amusement park for toddlers to 8 year olds).

Can easily see and experience the zoo and Adventure Landing in less than 6 hours.

#LetsGuide Tip: Be sure to ride the gondola as part of your experience, the panoramic Bay Area views are spectacular - can see all of the East Bay, Oakland Airport, San Francisco, etc.‚Äî there are bears, mountain lions, bald eagles, etc. to see, a cafeteria with self serve outdoor dining area a ‚Äúmultimillion dollar view,‚Äù and a zip line for kids to enjoy.

The zoo itself is hilly (many rolling hills) so if you are pushing a stroller or wheel chair it can be a workout.

Restrooms have diaper changing tables. Lots of outdoor dining areas that you can either purchase food or bring your own and eat.

Besides zoo ticket costs, parking cost is $10/car.

During the week, the place is filled with school groups and summer camp attendees besides families. There are certain areas where there can be a lot of kids in one place because of this.< /Text>

<text>I heard from many friends that this zoo was amazing and now I know first hand. Fantastic zoo for animals that can't be in their natural habitats with room to roam. The animals have space!!! Imagine that!?! And the prices are very reasonable (even has a discount online for membership- worth every cent and includes parking).
During this pandemic unfortunately a lot of exhibits are off limits and closed for obvious reasons but we still enjoyed  ourselves immensely and plan on coming back again soon. The zoo really needs the community's support to help sustain the animals needs.

When fully reopened (hopefully in the near future) there are kid play zones and viewing areas thoughtfully placed all around the park, an awesome gondola, a train and children amusement park area.
I didn't get to try the cafe (my only complaint) the cafe up near the Buffalo and bears was closed and I was starving and munching on my kids snacks üòê.</text>< Pics>

< text>
This zoo has improved so much since my last visit 15 years ago.  If you haven't been in many years, I encourage you to try again.  The animals were playing and seemed happy.  The enclosures were large with vegetation and structures suited to the animals inside. Great zoo for small children.  Only downside is that there are hills so hard for elderly and pushing strollers up hills with 2 children wasn't fun.  Kids loved the gondola up to California trail.<//text>

We did a walk-in.

Start your April Fool‚Äôs Day in Oakland Zoo. ü¶íü¶¨üêÜü¶ìü¶©ü¶ùüê´üêäü¶çüêòüê¢

Jun‚Äôs Tips:
1. Take a Bart and a Uber to the zoo.
2. Eat the Dipping Dots in the store (you rarely find it in supermarket; the banana split is good)
3. See the California Grizzly Bear. It‚Äôs the State bear.
4. Oversee SF and Oakland on top.
5. Eat their burger üçî in the canteen (the patty is moist like steamed. I like it. Not too dry or heated. )
6. Check out @christianlambertphoto for more photos of the Zoo.

Michael‚Äôs tip:
1. Go to the S.F. Embarcadero to talk about if you are going to come (you may not want to come)
2. Always love your husband.
3. Enjoy!

<user_name>Sarah Weessies< /user_name><Date>1583861299918< /Date><rate>5</rate><Review>The Oakland Zoo is a fun family oriented zoo. It would honestly be fun for a date as well. This zoo has a lot of options to see animals and learn. The gondola ride gives you a great view of the Bay area. There's a really nice place to eat at the top where the gondola drops you off. If it's a warmer day go in there. They always have it at a cool temperature and the food is amazing.< /Review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOSxyHBn9Pvkxy1KE-az9iHTOZcsB6lrlgBdMnz=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPnPvGnsDubSQ-FqM_dajdZIcCVW5jfcS7SAHfl=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNcqLHRTOfLwhVXPFTaCkMbYWl9KibK2s2LBxlb=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><response>{'time': 1583969649950, 'text': 'Thanks Sarah for the review!'}</response><gmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</gmapID></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
Admission price is 24 dollars and there is a mandatory parking fee of 10 dollars. The entrance is up far on purpose with no pedestrian access. When inside, there are some rides that require more fees. The food concessions are overpriced - bring food and water from home! The zoo itself is pretty decent and not dilapidated even if many animals look pretty old. However at these prices it's a place for the rich. The upper part with the gondola is actually quite nice but all day I had to think how much I will have to work to pay for the whole family to enter here :(<//Review>

<name>Bridgettes Product Reviews<//name><Rating>4</Rating><gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmap_id><response>None< /response><userid>107672969580771652443</userid><date>1582067852644< /date>< review>
I enjoyed the zoo. Be prepared to do a lot of uphill walking. It's pretty big for a local zoo. I advise bringing your own lunch and water. All the concessions were closed. Only a small gift shop was open. We were disappointed because we didn't get to see the lions, and a couple other exhibits were closed. The zoo does have a sky ride and an a gondola ride. Only one was working. There's a petting zoo for the kids. But only goats were available to pet. Toward the exit, there a small group of rides. A train, carousel, and some kids rides. It took us about 2.5 hours to walk and visit everything. So plan accordingly.</review>

< Review>
Elephants!! Wide open (albeit hilly) terrain with great social distancing.

Currently the Oakland zoo has free parking during the pandemic. A great way to spend a few hours exploring the animals. Our favorites were the elephants, bears, tigers, and lions.

The skytrain gives you a very expansive view of the entire Bay area, absolutely gorgeous views! Highly recommend visiting!!<//Review>

<date>1602577980922< /date><gmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmapID><resp>{'time': 1603471347859, 'text': 'Thanks!'}< /resp><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMpFkKcp30rW9UGQalzIz5c8KaI0FpJdpY6C60c=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNU_R_jI2nIupghliPkq26vuo2z3ogHUAsWt59l=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNEaoxQQQud_MWXCBtQCTb4aa27w_qq5oMEOTbK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>< UserId.>

<text>The Oakland Zoo is absolutely one of the best zoos in the Bay Area.  It is clean, well laid out, family friend, well kept and fun.  It is apparent that the animals are well cared for and a lot of thought has been put into their habitats.  It is very easy to spend the entire day walking this spacious zoo.

All of my life we have been coming to the Oakland Zoo and my memories of it are from childhood to adulthood are wonderful and precious.  We have take nieces, nephews and now grand-babies here.

The Oakland Zoo is a Bay Area Gem and it promotes wildlife education and conservation.  If you go to its website you can access their wildlife cameras and watch the Sun Bears, Black Bears, Elephants and Condors live.  It is an excellent place to spend a day relaxing individually or as a family and build your own special memories.  This is a must do if you are any type of animal lover!  Don't miss the train ride, merry-go-round or especially the Gondola/Sky-Hi ride that gives you spectacular views of the SF Bay Area.   We love this Zoo, its animals and the team of people who make this place so magically wonderful.  Enjoy!</text>< pictures>

<text>Have enjoyed the Zoo in the past, and had some trepidation about going anywhere during Covid, but they have several measures in place to limit exposure.  Reservations were easy to get online, and the limited number of people made it easy to stay distanced while seeing the animals.  The gondola was constantly being disinfected, and really enjoyed the new native California area up on the hill.  Good option for doing something outside with the family.< /text>< username>

V Tancredi</Name>
<Date>1566693349520</Date>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< text>
Decently large zoo with a great variety of different animals. Very family friendly, multiple Cafe's, play areas.

There's a mini amusement park at the top parking lot complete with a train.

In the last couple of years they made a great expansion to the crest of the Oakland hills. You take a wonderful gondola ride to the upper facility, where you are treated to constant panoramic views of the bay area.

There is a large cafe, play area and new exhibits of native fauna such as bears, wolves, mountain lions, condors, eagles etc.

They also have a buffalo area where they help raise buffalo to repopulate a herd being reinstated by a native American tribe.

If you do nothing else take the gondola ride and have a bite at the cafeteria. Most impressive.
Be prepared to take a walk for parking though. They have multiple large lots but the place is very very popular and gets crowded by families every weekend.</text>

<user>117238233440849797570< /user><text>The zoo is big and the animals have a lot of space to roam around. The giraffe area could be expanded though. There are already six of them plus other animals and the ducks. Their area seems small for so many animals. This zoo does not have as many animals as one would expect. Still a nice zoo. This year the area was expanded and the Gondolas were added. You could ride them up to a new cafeteria section for free. The view of the whole Bay Area is spectacular especially on a clear day. Food here is quite expensive. A cup of coffee costs almost $5.<//text></record>

<Name>Julian Roque<//Name>< rate>
5</rate>
<resp>{'time': 1583772488846, 'text': 'Just like us, some animals are not too fond of the rain :)'}< /resp><user_id>102526432032289515233<//user_id>< Gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//Gmap_id>
< review>
ProTip: Don't go when it's raining and/or cold. We went on a Saturday around 10:30 and it was lightly raining. The sign at the entrance said to decide if you want to go because the zoo might close. Luckily it didn't, but the animals weren't fans of the rain. The least kept up exhibit was the insect building; it also smelled pretty bad inside. Overall it was a good visit, especially the gondola ride to the California Trail. Also, to get a better view of the Bay than the bison overlook, go to the outdoor area of the nearby "visitor's center," which is actually a restaurant.< /review>

The tram to the new facility/restaurant is free and the food was suprisingly good. The staff was friendly and helpful. <text>In all fairness the day we went was windy so the gondola was not running, and there were horrendous fires burning just north. When the gondola is not working, you can only access a smaller part of the zoo. The upper part of the zoo was totally off-limits since there was no gondola ride to take you up there.  That's a whole third of the zoo . So we missed out on a lot. The air was thick and Smokey. But even beyond that, I was a disappointed in the zoo. It needs a lot of TLC. You can definitely tell it is an older Zoo. The animals look well cared for and there are a lot of well-informed docents to answer questions or provide information. Some of the things that weren't that great, were the lack of a signage to get you around the zoo, the many empty cages and enclosures, the poor quality of the ground you walk on, lots of big gaps and cracks and bumps that are kind of dangerous, lack of good signage on the foliage around the zoo which truly does make it interesting. And lack of any type of commentary on the little train ride that is given. There was no, "Welcome to the train ride", no standard, " keep your arms and legs in the train ride", not even descriptions of the animals that we slow down to see from the train. It definitely needs an overhaul. Better training on behalf of the people that provide the train ride too.</text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMdGfUVdDbDwbnb5enyATDSd3Xsdr9ObdqDm8m9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPt1HDVx8E3BPgmjJI_-xf8umtAGNLC0Br_EKkY=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8usqB7cw-WcFTOJYmZkJCiZrHxdOvitt1Z50_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPZO6l06l-A_6DVn7maXBCfvASB2jI88pcA0IvI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPALGrACLU2y41wjxkiMVbpDL68UP_gIa7Qvimd=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMl5OgZyc-XTDhgzM13-EjBc-momfdGg8sAH03o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMmXWokRuUq5PIjod9dfu7ImjJMTaHxSL3kCTLT=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO5pAIEeb3JAfI3DeicRP1YbJPbUOwIVti3fiis=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNd_MXGJIgXkS8FLqJcWLro1apl1YWNt6U6jN1U=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP_ZSgja2IZYaTGrZdzzjsLe07H1yAFVh7xyWWH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOVGwb25sSoC3qg3d4tmjgNhw6nWqsqw2K9Jept=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNpT01tZkaz7_Z9gbjQbrZk3EBiUDdm65xbwiVL=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< Resp>

< UserId.>
114870489657114807009</UserId.>
<Date>1522000604203</Date>< Review>
What a pleasant surprise! Oakland does not have the best reputation, and I figured that I might be disappointed. I was wrong. So wrong. The zoo is well-maintained, the animals were well cared for, and it was fin for both the adults and children. The California enclosures are currently being built, but you can take the gondola up to the top of the zoo property for a spectacular view. From the cafe you can see a HUGE section of the bay, including the ship yards, bridges, and the city below. It is a bit breezy up there to say the least, so make sure to bring a sweater on cooler days. The zoo is great for photographers, with both animals and beautiful gardens to capture. We did not have enough time to see everything, even though we were there for 3.5 hours. We pass through the area often and will definitely be back. San Francisco Zoo has some neat exhibits, but many of the buildings and habitats are closed and rotting away. SF Zoo is mostly flat, whereas the Oakland Zoo is carved into the side of a small mountain. I have mobility issues, and the hills wore me out, so plan some extra time to stop and rest along the way if you have difficulty walking or tire easily. This zoo reminded me a lot of the San Diego Zoo, albeit on a bit smaller scale.<//Review>

<Text>I've traveled to many zoos and this one remains one of my favorites. It has a nice variety of animals and interactive experiences for kids and adults alike. My family has had a family membership for the Oakland Zoo for the past five years, and I encourage everyone who wants to visit to buy a membership. Being a member gives you free parking, early notification of new events, and has reciprocal benefits at most zoos across the country. I also recommend arriving early if you want to see the lions and tigers active opposed to just sleeping in their habits.<//Text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP_V0AfoJmAHJC6LFt6aaGKRRgfODxkSBXetVBG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNCiGIZml_Kzg6CPejvop1GFDadylhqUbtf90Qt=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNLwtgdKy05NmP6QjAh6fYhrBLwG1kQ61qien1Q=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><Resp>None</Resp><gmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>

Great Zoo! The upper area, that can be reached with the gondola, is a must as this is what really completes the experience. The bottom part is a bit old and could be rejuvenated but the overall ambiance is not destroyed by these details that could be improved. <resp>{'time': 1597166951250, 'text': 'Thanks Brian for the great and thoughtful review! This is definitely a learning opportunity for us and feedback like this is extremely helpful in creating new protocols to keep our guests safe.'}</resp><text>We went Sunday August 2nd a few days after they opened again. Overall it was a great experience! The animals seemed more active than I remember, so maybe they were happy to see us again. Even the jaguar wasn't pacing.

The staff did a pretty good job considering the constraints they had to work under. They had people at various places directing everyone and I still saw many of them really enjoy talking with the guests while keeping safe.

There were a few downsides. While almost everyone wore a mask as directed, it was difficult at certain key places to keep 6 feet apart. Especially at the entrance there were a lot of people at the gift shop while we were trying to walk in. If they could temporarily move the gift shop somewhere else, that would be ideal I think.

Second, it was very difficult to keep kids from touching the glass. There are signs and people walking around reminding people not to touch the glass but it is difficult. Our kids did a fairly good job at it but still was very difficult to completely avoid.

Third, they did a great job cleaning each gondola as people got out, but the bottom had 3 separate lines and it was difficult for them to go in order and keep cleaning. I feel like they had the toughest job. They should do a single line at the bottom just like they do at the top.

Hopefully they are able to keep everything open, we would like to be able to keep going safely!</text></record></dataset><record>

<review>Excellent zoo. Reasonable price for admission and food. All around very clean. Even though I feel bad for most animals in zoo's the animals here had very spacious areas to roam, all enclosures were clean and filled with toys, ropes, etc. for activity and what I consider most important - private spaces. < text>
Great zoo, spread out so it doesn't feel crowded. The new California trail is a must see with lots of activities for kids. The bear exhibit was huge and we got to see the beard up close! My 5 year old spent a lot of time playing on the playground in the trail, and the cafeteria is a great place to lunch before heading back down the hill.

I highly recommend as a day trip, is even 2 days to split up the California trail and the rest of the zoo, but get there early so you don't have to worry about parking or stand in a huge line to ride the free gondola.</text>

<Text>Great way to spend an afternoon. Half a day should be enough time to get around and see the main things.
Some of the highlights for us were the Gibbons on their island. Be sure not to miss them.
A couple of other things worth seeing are the flying foxes on the way out are also definitely worth a visit ( mainly since you don‚Äôt see those very often) and also the reptile house (very nicely done with a few different terrariums and very active little guys to see).< /Text>< pictures>

< Review>
I was troubled by the lack of space the Oakland Zoo provides for the Bald Eagle. The Eagle expressed distress when I was last there. The Eagle would repeatedly fly to the top of the nettting as if trying to escape. Any sentient being desperately trying to escape to freedom is one of the saddest and traumatic things to witness.
The zoo does not provide nearly enough space for a bird that is known for flying at high altitudes.
I wish they would release the Eagle(s) to a more fitting and spacious animal reserve if there is no possibility of rehabilitation back into the wild.<//Review>

< rating>

< review>
I hadn't been to a zoo since I was a little kid and this one was quite fun and a chill experience. There was a wide variety of creatures to look at and I got the feeling they took good care of them. If you're looking for a relaxed way to spend an afternoon, this is the way to do it. They are opening a new section of the zoo in July that I didn't get to see but it looks very promising, with larger exhibits that try to place the animals in something more like their natural habitats. You even get to ride a lift with an amazing view up to the new area where there is a caf√© with the same view. We were able to go up to the caf√©, but not into the new area of the zoo.<//review>

<user_name>Vanessa Irene< /user_name><date>1576677071810< /date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
It is positively delightful, beautiful and very clean. It cost $24 for admission plus tax. Tickets can be purchased there and online. With this, it's free to ride the gondola up to the California Trail. Skyrides cost an extra $3. Note, it is really cold up there now(December) so dress appropriately. Also, make sure you wear comfortable shoes coz you will walk alot. Parking cost $10 so you can park across the zoo and walk to the gate. Finally, it is a fun place for adults and children. Enjoy!</Text>

<username>Mike Johnson< /username><text>I enjoyed the zoo very much. It seems well kept and well managed. It is a scenic walk even if there were no animals.  The big Surprise for me was the gondola ride to the east side of the park offering stunning views of the Bay. The structures on that side of the park were  beautiful including the cafe and the wooden decks/platforms made for walking, standing and viewing. I liked the environment throughout the zoo where the animals are kept (the enclosures) from The birds to the tigers.
What I didn't expect, was to have to pay $10 for parking. I also thought the admission fee might be less than what it was. I don't know what the average price of admission for zoos are Nationwide, but it seems a little high to me. Maybe it's just because I haven't been to a zoo in a while or maybe it's because it's located in California.<//text>< Pics>

<rating>4<//rating><text>Great zoo to take your family to. Easy access from the freeway. Parking  cost $10 per vehicle. Tickets are $25 for adults,  $20 per children.
Zoo location is on the side of the mountain,  so, there is many up and down walking trails, bring your comfortable shoes. The animals looks healthy, and good varieties. Good kids play area, and a petting yard.
Stop for lunch at Tusker Grill to enjoy a burger, or salad.  Try their Gilroy garlic fries.
Or, take the gondola ( free with your paid admission) to the California trail to enjoy your lunch, and see more animals after.  Make San Francisco bay overlook area as your last stop to enjoy a breathtaking view of the SF bay.</text>< pictures>

<user_id>103202217290338153417< /user_id><rate>5<//rate>< Text>
A Place where my grandparents visited while they were dating, and subsequent alternative to Fairyland, the Oakland zoo has held up well after, nearly a century of operation, and adapted with the times, and practices of some much bigger zoos in the United States.
One of our favorites was the Chimp there, (At least I think it was a chimp, hey what do you want, I was like, 5) who would mimic us kids and sometimes tag us with a piece of candy or a nutshell.
This is Oakland History. AND somehow still unknown to many younger East Bay residents. Change that! Go and visit!</Text>

I have come to enjoy very much Oakland's zoo  The first time the draught showed a terrible impact on the zoo's vegetation and animal and the ambiance was dusty but on February and may the park looked amazing and the animals also enjoyed the new condition as well. <review>The zoo has a lot to offer and doesn't take too long to walk around since it has the distinct areas. We started off with the Sky Ride (an extra $3 per person) and got to see over the giraffes, lions and elephants. From there we went to see the baboons, siamang and monkeys and birds. They have a really nice collection of insects, but there were only a few reptiles in the other area. The black bears, grizzly bears and meerkat were all resting so they weren't out when we hit the exhibits.

Overall it was a fun visit on the 1st or January. <username>Pradeep Varadan</username>< gmapID>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmapID>
<Time>1531924334111<//Time>< Review>
While at the outset , I was unsure of what fan fare to expect for a hefty $24 entry fee , I was pleasantly surprised at what the zoo had to offer. Starting with the maps which my toddler could interpret owing to the animal silhouettes that line up, through the Australian safari on a clickety clack steam train, up the sky ride over the lion, camel and the elephants, going further up to the enclosed gondola giving not only a magnificent view of the cities,but also taking one to the California Trail, the zoo just rocks.

From a toddler's perspective it was sheer delight given the fact that I eased his walks with a stroller to go everywhere. The trails are covered with greenery making the walks a non issue even on a hot day. Conveniently placed stores , restrooms and water stops make enjoying the animals your only option! I was impressed with the magnificence of the African section with the Giraffes, Elephants and Elands.

I would highly recommend this place for a full day trip with your family. The well maintained trails, the carefully manicured enclosures with ample space and human created mimicry of natural features like stone walls, deserts, water falls etc along with geographically apt flora make the fauna come to life.<//Review>

< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<review>The covid protocols are pretty simple to navigate and reassuring. Buy tickets or reserve with your membership online and have them printed or on your phone when you arrive. The Baboon bridge gets too crowded to be safe, if that's a special one for your kid(s) be aware it may not be on the itinerary. The mask rules for kids are above and beyond state recommendations (a good thing, most kids can keep a mask on), however the staff did not harass me when my developmentally disabled child who is older than 3 refused to keep his mask on halfway through our visit. We were able to distance further from people at that point because it is not crowded at all. Gondolas are sprayed with disinfectant after each use and hand sanitizer is provided before boarding. All in all a very stress free outing after months of staying home.</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< resp>

<Review>Oakland zoo is large and you can easily spend the WHOLE day here. Wear some comfortable shoes, some of the paths will be going uphill/downhill. Bring a stroller for younger children as they may get tired from walking, but it you forget it, they do have stroller rentals available. Bathrooms are located throughout the park as well as drinking stations and food kiosks. There are several feeding times throughout the day and trainer talks. They have an app you can download that helps with the schedules and also map of the zoo. They have a new California trail that recently opened. You'll have to take a skyline ride to get to it. There are also several kids play area throughout so you can let them play run around a bit and you can sit have a break lol< /Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOXnN1mZ-lLftHItLuJJRlwKM_S1Of388Q603lM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPh1StcF52-6kscS7Ol9wc0yhLKop8gynVDsir4=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMgmrzO9V3FCagOlAFkkI9fJ2eY4-EA2cVq_C8w=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPcekp1xJLHfxsqT_6M2lsmZfVeYEpXJOYywINu=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMQ5jx9fsVRcO8-VKIon1T8hL7WaNWWeWmpPyqk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNRhXO38LkAVjuEVd22c84aN4OFXbF4wicKPgJG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOqlVgxAQgL3ixc2sSqcZMQzRw6bHlfU8h7TAkS=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNiQe2Wo_9J2dvyhILiDBf_tWI-vgcJF3NoQ4NU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><Rate>5</Rate><UserId.>113520200107396087494</UserId.><resp>None</resp><Date>1536326282343<//Date>< name>

< text>
COVID UPDATE: A sizable portion of the zoo is closed as of the writing of this review. All of the drinking fountains are closed so expect to bring your own water or prepare to purchase the aluminum water bottles.

Only one refill station is available immediately after the gondola.

Masks on all the time rule was okay with me and my party but may be difficult for those with breathing problems especially on hot days like when I went (93¬∞F).

If you want to support the zoo, think about donating via their website. Otherwise, save your money for the full reopening.<//text>

< text>
Went to the zoo this october and it was really nice. The zoo limits the number of people who can come to the zoo through their reservation system online and the entrance fee is not expensive at all. There is few exibits for food near the entrance (which closes by 3pm) and a stand that sells snacks inside so either pack a lunch for your family or eat before going to the zoo. Any part of the zoo that is enclosed is closed. The animals seem to love it since it's very quiet. We enjoyed it and spent about 4 hours there. Plenty of areas with sanitizer stations.<//text>

<rate>5< /rate><text>So fun! We have annual family passes and they paid for themselves in just 3 visits. Since we don't have to pay every time we go in we pop by for lunch (the food is really lame but the view is unbeatable), take friends and family, ride the gondola at sunset.

I love the giraffes, elephants, hilarious monkeys, bats, camels. The baboons are AWESOME , always running around, playing tag, wrestling. And there's all ages from a tiny baby baboon that hangs out on it's mom's back to a big cool old dude who just chills while the others wait on him all day.

The kids area at the Oakland zoo is perfect, too --both my 3 yo niece and 9yo nephew could both really enjoy almost all the rides (he was too tall for just one of them). And they have a Little Free Library on one of their nature paths!</text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNxfdgd_BAVxeFcVrdo2GB5HYPjZZwFtb6XAlJt=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMsXHnqYjJYxTNCpqT0vfuntjkjF56Uq-Os_8QE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPVYxqVL1CEvn3ilOu4-7eM4BlRSnMoj1tYKQfc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNT4LzpAuuR5_2HyYlT79lodTSPZFk_WvPvCXrI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP30wTmNMNUowgsA_bzSuoVpMPfZu_Mqvh_Dr2i=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPSvuB6bAJX3dOIhBswtPHCvUqrtVZSGcTR8pfg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMBq6KUIyiNB6UVIH0wlc144GtzJb1jAWDRPqOt=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>< response>

< review>
If you are in Bay Area, do not miss out this place. I like the size of this considering the kids you are bringing in with. Open gandola will take you to one side of the allowing you have birds eye view of the zoo whereas new gandola- cable car- is new addition. The cafe at top of the zoo site gives a breathtaking  view of bay area and pacific ocean. Definately recommended.</review>

1551730921952< /date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
This zoo went through a recent expansion adding what is known as the California Trail.  Basically more than doubling the previous Zoo size.  Bald Eagles, Condors, Cougers, Black Bears, Grizzly Bears and more.  Keep in mind this in addition to what was previously there, like Tigers, Lions, Elephants, oh my and more.  With the expantion comes a higher price too, but you get to see so much more as well.  An added bonus is the views of San Francisco are pretty awesome from this new portion of the Zoo.<//Text>

Five stars.  It was beautiful zoo.  I'm so surprised how big the areas were.  I enjoyed the gondola ride and seeing the gorgeous view of the bay, I would recommend everyone to come here and I would come back.   Also, be sure to check your library's Discover and Go program for free admission AND parking (Tues-Thurs only!) We scored both, which saved us a chunk of money.  Arrive early for parking and bring sunglasses, a hat and bottled water, especially if it's sunny out.</review>

<Text>Heard some good things from friends and the reviews on Google.  There is also the Oakland Zoo App.  I have to say we had a great time exploring everything that the zoo had to offer.
All the employees we interacted with were very nice and friendly.  Some of the enclosure's are very large and like the lions, they hang out in the back where it might be hard to seeing them through the telescopes.  I would suggest to ride the 'Sky Ride' it's $3 each, you get a great view of the lions, giraffes, camels and bison.  Take the  gondola to a cafe, visitor center and the second part of the zoo, with the all new areas that opened in 2018.  Really enjoyed the Grizzly enclosure huge with lots of viewing areas.<//Text>< time>

1504836908713< /date>
< Rate>
5< /Rate>
< text>
Love the Oakland Zoo! The animals have large enclosures and the zoo keepers are always out and about willing to discuss animal diets and habits with children. The new gondola takes you to a whole new conservation walk area and restaurant. Start with the flamingos and turn right to walk counter clockwise around the zoo path. Tigers, giraffes, camels, lions, birds, elephants, zebras, meercats, hyenas, wart hogs, baboons, crocodiles, bugs, petting zoo, pigs, goats, sheep, bats, otters, turtles, lemurs, giant tortoises, toucans, monkeys, sun bears (often hiding in that beautiful enclosure), deer and more I'm sure I missed. Fun to enjoy again and again. Buy a family membership for free parking and more discounts.<//text>

Great zoo for all ages! We come here often with our toddler to make the best of our membership and spend some family time together.
Only quip is if you have an outside drink they will not allow lids or straws but conveniently have both in their cafes.

**Update**
I‚Äôm glad that you are no longer using the lids and straws in the cafe keeping the plastic pollution in mind and for the safety of the animals. Next time I shall carry my reusable glass for my own drink.< /review>

<user_id>108721012908510707798< /user_id>< username>
Bella Fica< /username>
< date>
1556333290910< /date>
< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< text>
The Oakland Zoo spans some 100 acres and is home to over 750 native and exotic animals. I was not prepared for the hills, inclines and stairs to get in between exhibits. It is nice that there are live people guides to help direct you places and discuss the animals. Visitors can take a train ride and discover the Wild Australia section for emu and wallaroos. The African Savanna area is where the popular giraffes, zebras, and elephants are located.  There are two aerial rides.  The Sky Ride which you have to pay an extra $3 to ride and the gondolas that take visitors to the California Trail and visitor center. There is a panoramic San Francisco Bay overlook worth the wait in line and trip.  There is a lot to see and do at the Oakland Zoo, we did not get to everything this visit but I look forward to the next.< /text>

I was blown away by the views you get at this zoo! The gondolas give you views not only if the bay, but if the animals below you like the lions and the camels. There are many animals to see, and they seem to be well taken care of with lots of space. I also highly recommend coming for the light show during the winter holiday. They put a lot of effort into decorating the park, and it is a treat to take the rainbow light gondola at night.< /review>

A great zoo with a lot of different animals, spread out over a vast area. Memories as a kid involved the San Francisco Zoo, but I have to say that it is not match compared to the Oakland Zoo. We took the sky gondola to the aminal habitat area, and it was nice to be able to see wolves and other animals in such a large area, but still be observable by patrons. Some great veiws of the Bay as well. My son really enjoyed the different rides available.< /Review>

< text>
The Oakland Zoo is an average Zoo.The species are neither very rare or exotic. Three lions, three tigers, four elephants, 6-7 Giraffes may not make it a world class. Amphibians, reptiles, Birds section was a total disappointment. Though crowded the entry fees and parking fee make it a costly affair. The visitors galleries need quantum improvement for visitors and little children  to have a good look at animals without disturbing  them. The Gandola and train ride can be enjoyed only if exotic varieties and large wild  animals are in plenty.<//text>

<user_id>100318707557205030113<//user_id>< Name>
Vishal Mehta< /Name>
<time>1577225549633</time><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Rating>4</Rating><gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//gmap_id>< review>
Best zoo in Bay Area!

The design of the exhibits makes it easier to spot animals more naturally. Although there are fences and glass and nets where required, but the experience is friendlier than other zoos I have visited. The size is perfect for completing the tour in a few hours satisfactorily, covering all exhibits.

First thing I would recommend is the Gondola ride, which takes you to the top level of the zoo. Complete that level exhibits and return to the lower level to enjoy the rest.

Food and drinks are allowed, which makes it easier for families to plan. There are plenty of benches and sheltered spots where you can relax and eat before moving on to the viewing.

Unfortunately, the petting zoo and a couple of exhibits were closed due to rainy weather.< /review>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
So much to see and do. You can have a different experience each time you go. Take the gondola to the upper zoo where you'll find a new set of animals to see, an outdoor and indoor play area for kids (including a very popular zipline), and a place to eat. Back down on lower zoo, there's a petting zoo, play area, places to picnic, and a place with rides for kids (train, carousel etc). We go all the time and never get bored.</review>

<text>I've generally hated zoos.  Many zoos have that heartbreaking quality of visiting a prison.  The Oakland Zoo is a bit refreshing in that the animal habitats are generally large and well-appointed, the animals are mostly rescues, and the staff that I've interacted with are passionate and knowledgeable.  It's a nice, sprawling zoo.  Check out the Siamangs and the Flying Foxes (the world's largest fruit bats!).< /text></record></dataset><record>

This is during Covid...but not entirely related to it.
Pros
-Easy in an out with buying tickets online!
-Nice to see large areas for the Animals!
-Clean bathrooms an areas
- Not gonna complain about exhibits being closed or animals not there etc. Life goes on lol.
-Taking the gondola is cool but read my con lol.

Cons however ....
-I get some food places need to be closed. But there wasn‚Äôt a single vender in the park. Maybe I missed the one right as you walk in. But through the entire park. Not a single food or drink station. I would have left sooner simply to get food, but just trying to walk to every attraction takes forever.

-Complete nightmare walking with a stroller or a child you have to carry. Pathways are uphill or down hill and most areas are a one way in one way out. This is not cause of Covid. It‚Äôs just how the path is. So you have to walk one way to see something to then walk back to get to something else. Poor planning on the layout for sure. Not a single flat area...

-The gondola ride was fun for the kids. A stroller takes up space. Everything was closed or empty but the bears an bison. The bison don‚Äôt do anything an the bear exhibit is the only exhibit worth it. There is also no shade. So unless you wana see a few bears. You can totally skip this. The restaurant is also closed. So no food.

-Not sure of the whole point of a parking pass as it wasn‚Äôt left in my car nor attached to my plate. So I hope that $10  goes to the zoo lol.

Over all it‚Äôs a one an done kinda thing. I enjoyed the Zoo an I am glad they were able to open back up. I didn‚Äôt mind the lack of exhibits etc. I minded the poor planning of the layout of Exhibits an the lack of food and drink.< /Review>

< text>
*Australia area+train ride are extra
*need special key to listen to animal information
* gondola ride included (freaky but worth it)
*great views of animals
*playground in upper area...
It was our first time visiting this zoo and we went on a cloudy, on-and-off raining day so the  animals were all really active and fun to watch.
We got to be really close to a lot of the animals but there were many enclosures with nothing in them or where we couldn‚Äôt see anything (apes, wolves, plus others) which was disappointing.
We were also disappointed that we couldn‚Äôt see any of the Australian exhibit without paying extra to get on the train. There were a lot of us and we‚Äôd already paid a lot to get in to the zoo so we had to skip that.
There was not a lot of information on the signs throughout but there were little speaker boxes. We couldn‚Äôt figure out how to get the speaker boxes to work until we came across a key someone had dropped that made them play!!</text>

<Time>1553319982145<//Time><Rating>5< /Rating><text>Despite going on a weekend that was WAY too crowded (it took 30 minutes just to get off the freeway because the zoo parking lot was so backed up...pretty sure everyone was trying to use their Groupon coupons before they expired), it was a great spot. Beautiful location, good variety of animals, clean facilities. Our daughters loved it, especially seeing Simba and Mufasa (see pics). The only part we didn't do was the California area, but that's because it was in an area only accessible by gondola, and we didn't feel like waiting in the long line and leaving our double stroller with all of our stuff behind (because it wouldn't have fit on the gondola). We'll go back and see that when the girls are older. Overall, definitely worth checking out, though.</text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMrKJvCns67e5TgwTQjkLuAhlpao0ezLhNT6Dw2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOKO_3ndPL7JLsEQkXP4Tl2woToFCVp1-gkrBqI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPimNwIieMdA07QfQ88AkIjOJ66i0Ss_EBRL5zQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><resp>{'time': 1553531731026, 'text': "Thanks for the review Matthew. This is a great place to bring your kids. They have so many animals and if you come in the morning they are usually active. The gondola ride to the top is also very good as you get the view of the bay. And the ride is free! You'll get to see the bald eagle, wolves, jaguar, bears and mountain lions. This is a fun place for the entire family!< /text>

< username>
Travis Carroll< /username>
< review>
The Oakland Zoo is a beautiful zoo, and riding the gondola to see rest of the park (California Trail ) and the views is a must! It's nice to see a lot of the animals in large areas and they all appear to be very happy. It's a great place for kids and families. We packed a lunch and had a little picnic while being there, highly recommended over waiting in line for lunch. Parking can be a bit chaotic, so I would recommend going during the time they first open, or a few hours later when people start leaving. We went on a cold day, so we weren't able to see the bears but maybe next time!</review>

What a great place for a weekend gateway with family and friends. All the animals are very healthy and well managed. They also have very friendly staff around, and a well mix of mammals, reptiles and birds, and of course bugs. The only downside is the parking space constraints , and the place can get really busy over weekend and expect to spend quite sometime to find parking spot.</text>

This is our second time at the zoo after a few years. Our first experience was not so great but this time around we had a great time. Getting there early was the key as the animals were more out and about rather than hiding in the shade.

Also the gondola ride to California trail was pretty cool with bears and bison on display. In addition a nice little play area for the kids. Kids and us had a great time, signed up for the annual membership!!!<//review>

< review>
Great zoo! It complements the SF Zoo nicely given some different animals. Oakland notably has elephants, baboons gibbons, buffalo camels, alligators and a jaguar. The skylift ride, gondola and kids ride park are nice additional attractions for kids and the whole family. Highly recommend the family membership packages which are great deals - the family membership we got cost a lot less than two visits.</review>

<userid>102367680813049234813< /userid><rating>5</rating><gmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /gmapID>< review>
This was fantastic! Free parking was an unexpected surprise. We had a blast of a FUN workout, as we strolled through the lighted Zoo. There was something for everyone's interests.
The light show was fun to watch as the lights changed and seemed to dance with the Christmas music. The Christmas song choices were just as diverse as the attractions throughout the Zoo.
I do recommend this holiday Zoo Lights show for your Christmas, to do list! And, also...
Just remember to remove your plastic lids on your soft drinks/coffee cups before entering. Their not allowed.
Enjoy, Merry Christmas World!
Thanks Oakland Zoo!!<//review>

< text>
This zoo is beautiful and great to visit year round. There is a ton of shade on hot summer days and a great new play area for kids in the new California Trail area. They have lots of benches to rest while you view the animals and several spots to eat if you bring your own picnic lunch. Food and rides at the zoo are pricey but the proceeds all go back into the zoo and their many charities so totally worth it.</text>

< Review>
I've never been to the San Diego zoo which by most accounts is the best zoo in the country but I have been to several others and this is by far the best zoo I've ever been to. I went in with high expectations and I was not let down. What an incredible experience, it seems a lot of thought was put into this zoo and the only complaint I have is that while most of the enclosures seem appropriate to the animals inside, the chimpanzee enclosure seems way to small for them, especially considering all the open space not far away that could be used to expand the chimp enclosure.<//Review>

Perfect size zoo for my two year old. We had a really great time watching the bears. We got there on a Saturday at 11AM. There was a long line to wait for the parking lot entry. The lot was full, and we were instructed to park alongside the curb driving up to the lot. We got on the Gondola first which I highly suggest for two reasons. 1) the line is short, and 2) the other park is small. There's also  The California Wilds Playground on that side which has a sandpit, a small Creek for littles to stick their toes in, a Zipline, a small tunnel and a slide. We then came back to the main park and finished our visit there.<//Text>

< userid>
101531998794144797609< /userid>
< Review>
Location on a hill in Oakland off I580.
It should be arguably the best zoo in Bay Area and nearby.
Very reasonably priced, it offers a free Gondola ride up the mountain ( not to be missed) too!!
With our family of four and with 2 kids, we were able to experience 80% of the zoo in 4 hours. We did not do the other sky ride ( paid service). A paid train trip also adds to excitement but it is a very  short ride.
There are about four rides ( carousel, plane, etc) which are OK priced at train station.
It has a reasonable collection of animals and most impressive to us were the primates. The park has lot of birds out of cage and in the wild.  For bird photography, I found ample opportunities. Park has decent food options and several picnic areas.
Overall a good half day trip. Since there are activities too other than exhibits, you could plan multiple trips in the year.<//Review>

<name>Roy West< /name>< rating>
3< /rating>
<Date>1561474440996<//Date><user_id>105988730002336504786< /user_id>< text>
This priceless last piece of quiet, unspoiled open space in the Oakland hills has been replaced with a restaurant and animal cages,  denuding the meadows and killing the oaks and even locally rare native plants. The buildings, views, and animal displays are attractive and informative. It's just hard to enjoy them understanding the cost to Oakland's native ecosystems.< /text>
<pictures>None<//pictures><GmapID>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /GmapID>< response>
{'time': 1561566811828, 'text': "Hi Roy. We understand your concern but with the building of California Trail we actually made sure to preserve a lot of the native fauna and flora. Our elevated pathways help preserve the local grassland, marine chaparral, and oak woodland. We made sure to build our aviaries and habitats high enough that we wouldn't have to cut down the trees. We have set up trap cams that also monitor all local wildlife around the zoo. We hear you and share your concern and want to assure you we are helping preserve the local fauna and flora. Thank you for leaving this review. If you would like to discuss more, please email web@oaklandzoo.org ."}</response>

<review>The zoo itself is awesome. The kids loved it. The new gondola lift is really great. It is fast, quiet and you get to see absolutely beautiful scenery view of the entire Bay Area while you ride you ride up and back down to and from the top. At the top are all of the new exhibits. California mountain lion was only inches away.  The zoo is a large area and the paths are fun to walk through. They have several types of animals and are currently expanding with more enclosures and different animals.</review></record>

1538052342327<//Date>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
Way better than the San Francisco zoo, and half the price. You can spend hours here, especially with little ones. They just opened a whole new section of wild animals that you can go see with a gondola ride to the top of the mountain. I'm a member here, and the price wasn't bad at all. Three visits and it already paid for itself. You can bring in your own food to save on costs, and they even have a baby amusement park for little ones!<//Review>

< Review>
Overall great zoo! Nice and spacious, lots of little spots for tots to play such as, the lily pad walk, and otter slide by the crocs, and the spider web by the Bug House. Good selection of food at the cafe. Cost was a little high, however, it goes to a worthy cause so I would expect to pay a little more. Staff were all very nice and informative. < review>
Nice place to spend time with your family and friends. Be ready to walk because this place is huge. The exhibit is huge and very safe, be careful with the chimps they're very smart they sometimes throw feces at people who dare to get too close and sometimes hit bystanders. You're warned. They have bears, monkeys, chimps, hyenas, crocodiles, lemurs, elephants, camels, turtles, flamingos, reptiles, insects, jirafs,etc. They have children activities, a little museum elevator, handicap ramps, restrooms, restaurants, aereal gondolas a little train ride, mechanic rides, penny press machines and a gift shop.< /review>

<Review>The zoo has undergone many improvements over the years.  Recently it has added a section on California animals.  The plus side is that it is well laid out, the animals are in natural habitats (which means that they can be really hard to see, they blend in to the grasses, hills, and trees) ...so be prepared to stand around and look for awhile.  This area is only accessible by an overhead cable car.  The plus of this is that it has great views and is fun.  The disadvantage is that the lines can get rather long, especially on Fridays in the summer.
The animal exhibits are well done and many are natural, elephants have hills, lions really really blend into the hillside.
The children's area has lots of play structures to tire the kids out, as well as child oriented animal exhibits (the otters are really popular.)
A good way to spend a day with the family.<//Review><pictures>None</pictures><resp>{'time': 1565631560544, 'text': 'Thanks for the detailed review'}<//resp>< Gmap_id>

<Review>Good place for very young kids, ages 3-6. I liked the sea otters the most as well as the gondola ride. I still haven't checked out the new upper portion of the zoo or the reptile house, and will save those for a later date. I did thoroughly appreciate the layout of the zoo and how much space the animals were given. They out a lot of thought into keeping the animals happy. My review is mainly for the membership. This membership is only worth it if you have a family with very young children and you live close to the zoo. I thought it was a well-thought out scam that the amount paid for parking on the day you buy your membership isn't applied towards your membership (since you get free parking with membership) instead you can either apply that amount towards the few dinky rides outside of the zoo or just eat the cost. It is partially my fault for buying a membership my first time at the zoo, without reading further into the consequences of buying a membership.

I am an auntie to about a million children, I have no children of my own, and thought to use the membership to bring my various comadres and their kids to the zoo so we could all spend the day together. I was annoyed that I had to buy the more expensive family plus membership (rather than the regular family), since you have to name both adults, and I needed a membership that would allow myself, 1 adult guest, and several child guests. If I weren't already there with a gaggle of kids, and if I hadn't already paid for parking, I would have just left and not bought the membership.

If you're going to buy a new membership, I would suggest buying the membership online first to avoid the additional cost of paying for parking or just take the bus there.</Review></record>
