0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id>
<review>The good:  I really appreciated the wide variety of animals and exhibits that were on display when I visited, and the zoo's commitment to conservation work and animal welfare seems genuine.  I especially appreciate how they are working with the Siksika/Blackfoot nation to reintroduce wild bison, their rehabilitation of injured and orphaned animals, as well as providing a home for animals who were illegally bought as a pets.

The bad:  I came here with a friend who needed to use a wheelchair, and I was astonished at not only how inaccessible huge areas of the park are to people with disabilities but also how poorly information about accessibility was communicated.  There are wheelchairs available for rent, but they cost $15 (not including a $20 refundable deposit).  Similar museums either charge nothing aside from a deposit or just ask for a photo ID as a security measure.  Even though the wheelchair costs $15 to rent, there is only one size available and it is hard to maneuver.  The only reason it was usable to my friend is because I was available to push it.  Because the wheelchair has non-removable sides, it was very difficult to self-propel even on flat surfaces.  It was completely impossible to self-propel uphill, which is a large portion of the park.  Additionally, many areas of the park are completely inaccessible to non-ambulatory wheelchair users.  My friend was able to walk a short distance with a cane to visit these areas, but not everyone who uses a wheelchair is able to do this.  Given the large number of signs available to orient visitors, it is shocking to me there is no information about which paths might be most accessible, where elevators to avoid stairs could be found, or cautionary information about paths that might have slopes that would be difficult for people with mobility-related disabilities.  The information provided about storing and maneuvering the park with a stroller was far more comprehensive than the instructions provided to individuals in wheelchairs.  I understand that the zoo was started before the ADA, but many of these fixes are relatively simple (e.g., adding informative signage, adding buttons to automatically open doors, installing wider doors).  Given all of these issues relating to navigating around the park, the very least the managers could do is provide wheelchairs for free conditional on providing a security deposit or leaving an ID card.  Other local museums provide wheelchairs for free, and a $35 initial payment is excessive in light of the $24 admission fee that is charged for entering the zoo.<//review>< Date>
1577493107981<//Date>
</record>
</dataset><record>

< text>
It was going to be a quick family trip, but we ended up making a day of it, ~ 4.5 hours at the zoo. For being on a very busy day, it didn't feel incredibly crowded, besides busy, but easy parking, when we rolled up at noon. There was a stacked line for the adventure landing train, $3.50 / person, but we timed everything else really well. If you have to choose, the take flight lift at $3 / person is a much better experience for animal viewing and relaxing than the train. The gondolas are free, and fast!, to take you to the new, and pretty big, area. We went to the new area with the zoo open for another hour and had plenty of time including playing at the playground up there.< /text>

< Text>
I've been to quite a few zoos over many states and even in different countries, and I have to say the Oakland Zoo is my favorite. The animals just seem happy. I always have good sightings of lions, tigers, elephants, hyenas, and lemurs. Now, with the new California Trail it's even better. I was so impressed on our recent visit about the areas for the grizzly bears, mountain lions, wolves, jaguar, and bison. I love how the walkways at this Zoo wind around with all the trees and through the hillsides. It never seems crowded because it's so spread out. There really is something for everyone at this zoo, highly recommended.<//Text>

< review>
The Oakland zoo is fairly well maintained. Some of the animal's habitats seen smallish (giraffes, chimpanzee's) . Only one elephant out at the exhibit.The gondola ride to the California trail was the highlight of the entire trail experience. It did have quite a bit for  smaller children to climb on . The Australian train ride was worth the extra money. This zoo is on the lower end of the spectrum for Adult customers. I would rate it higher for children who like rides and diversions.</review>

<review>Nice zoo. Most the enclosures are spacious. The animals were active. Lots of docents were available to answer questions. We went on an overcast partly rainy day in spring: the train, most the concessions, and the rides were not open due to weather, but we were able to park close in the parking lot and there were no crowds. Highly recommend riding the gondola up to let the kids play on the playground- great nature theame playground for all ages with amazing views and excellent California history on top. 114634809026858215027</user_id>
<name>Dennis Smith<//name><time>1530330763553< /time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< Text>
I love going to the Oakland Zoo, they have lots of animals to see and fun things for the kids to to do. There's a train that takes you around a section of the property, a cable car system that takes you up and over the lions and giraffes to another section of the park with a great view of both Oakland and San Francisco cities from the cable cars.

They also have a new cable car system that takes you on top of the hill to a beautiful restaurant and lovely view of the two cities. The staff all around the zoo are always very friendly and seems to be very knowledgeable about the animals, you'll see them hanging out around some of the main area of the zoo to answer any questions about the animals or to give directions to the to the guests.

Overal, the Oakland Zoo is a wonderful  little treasure in the city of Oakland which attracts visitors from all around the world.

Have fun at the zoo!! I hope this helps.< /Text>

< userid>
103698158638735758566< /userid>
< text>
The vegetation is lovely around the Zoo although it would be nice to have more trails to take various ways to different exhibits. The animals had well sized and varied enclosures  only problem was vegetation was lush enough to make some hard to find in exhibits.

The Gondola ride was highlight of trip and it will be nice to visit when paths and exhibits are open at the top. The best dining was at the top yet it was always crowded so hopefully they will add more seating, especially outside with the view. That was very limited. It would be a great setting for an evening event at the Zoo and it would be fun to see an adult type event utilizing the spectacular view of the Bay Area and San Francisco.

We were fortunate to have perfect weather. Just enough breeze and temperate weather to make it very comfortable. It might get hot in mid-summer since it's exposed in areas and away from the coast. It's a great place to spend an active day with family.</text>

<Text>Good place for a family day trip. The main zoo part is fun to traverse because the trail goes up and down and through trees and brush. I felt like I was walking through Jurassic Park. It's nice and big with lots to see and some grassy areas to run around in or have a picnic lunch. There's a new part of the zoo that's only accessed by a gondola ride up the foothills. Once you're up there it's this huge deck that goes around the perimeter and you look down into the enclosures to see the wolves or whatnot. There's an area for the kids to play and climb on stuff.

The cons of visiting here though is that first off it's not nearly as aesthetic as the SF zoo. They've left it pretty overgrown and natural which isn't a bad thing per ces but it does feel a little out of control. Also, there were a lot of exhibits that were closed and empty. If they can't put an animal there then they should clear it for picnic benches or playgrounds. The bathrooms were a wreck! Dirty and a lot of non functional sinks/dispensers/etc. And lastly, there was literally 2 benches to sit down on to rest or just watch an animal up in the newer area and the whole area is pretty much in the sun. So as cool as the new area is, it was pretty miserable to visit when you couldn't sit down and rest for 5 minutes or get out of the sun<//Text>< gmap_id>

< Text>
Not so big, but big enough to spend a day (10am to 4pm).. Love the Tigers, Lions and Elephants there, Other interesting animals there are Giraffe, Camel, Alligators, Tortoise, Chimpanzee, Zebra, Small python, Kangaroo(by train), birds and more.. Free gondola rides, the small one goes over Tigers and Lions, by Camel, Giraffe and Elephants, the big one takes you to a restaurant and another area that is opening in summer 2018.. The kids rides are not free with the entrance tickets, costs ~$2 to $4 per ride. Train ride is $3.5 per person . OR I think you can pay extra $24 for all the rides. Parking extra $10.</Text>

< Review>
Great zoo, new gondola is amazing!  There are a lot of hills, so it's moderately strenuous to spend the day there.  Apart from the zoo (separate, but adjoining) is a small amusement park for younger kids.  The little train is very cool, as it enters the zoo and gives an up close view of some of the Australian animals as well as beautiful views of the whole Bay Area (on a clear day).  Views from the new gondola station are great too, but it gets windy up there, so bring a jacket!  Hope this helps you plan your visit.<//Review>

<time>1577558843333< /time><rate>5<//rate><Text>This is a terrific zoo! While it is not the San Diego zoo, it is far superior to the San Francisco Zoo. It has very natural large enclosures for the animals and seems to incorporate various aspects of the land. The addition of the gondola and the California wildlife exhibit at the top of the hill is amazing. I love how it seems as though the enclosures are really nothing more than an untouched  patch of native land including namesake Oak trees. My favorite animal is the jaguar, which my 18 month old daughter referred to as a kittykat when it was locked eyes with her six inches from the glass. I jokingly informed her that kittykat was looking at her like a snack. The highlight of the medium sized play area is the zipline. There is always a line of parents and kids waiting for there chance to send their kids flying down into a quintet of springs that stop the flyer less violently than other ziplines I have seen and ridden. Great selection of animals with Africa making the most prolific appearance. Overall it is an awesome zoo and I highly recommend it.<//Text>< Pics>

Awesome zoo with a great variety of animals. Nice enclosures and well laid out, with things to interest children and grown ups.  Plenty of amenities and also a train ride and gondola, which were both fun and let you see parts of the zoo which would not have been accessible otherwise. <userid>104785550709624237102< /userid>< pictures>

<rate>4</rate><Time>1556155109024< /Time></record></dataset><record>
< gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</gmap_id>
<pictures>None< /pictures>< review>
Mismanaged and disorganized, but the kids don't care! Also, member tips included!

I'll start by saying we are members of the OZ, and have been for years. We believe in the mission and the kids love it - zoo lights, the gondola, the new California experience, the rides, and every single animal habitat... truly, they LOVE IT.

Here's the but, and this hopefully is constructive... It is poorly managed. You can tell this is a culture thing. It comes from the top down. Keep in mind that the members and visitors really only see and interact with the service staff. Not the zoo keepers, not the management, but the people running the show. It is abundantly clear that they are just there to push a button or advance a line or sling a chicken tender. They are not there to be helpful or usually even polite. In fact, most of them are on their phones and, if they even look at you, it looks as if their very souls are being crushed if you deign to ask where the restroom is. Crushed.

The volunteers, on the other hand, are usually the opposite and go out of their way to provide info, chat up your kids, or just make sure you're enjoying yourself. Strangely, not paid.

Anyway, as promised, here is the local/member tips part: if you don't have kids in tow, do whatever you like, unencumbered and free to enjoy without a million bathroom and snack breaks! If, like most of us, you have at least one young child in tow, lucky you! Seeing this world through the eyes of a child is pure magic, so:
1. Arrive by 10am. Forget nap. Park in the upper lot nearest the main entrance. If you arrive past 10am on a weekend there's a good chance you're parking in the lower lot of having to walk some insane distance up a crazy hill.
2. Bring a stroller with storage space or a wagon, snacks, plenty of water/juice boxes (for bribery), and a full meal. Also a blanket.
3. It's usually good weather in the hills, so bring layers, but plan to be warmer than colder. Sunglasses, hats, and sunscreen help a lot.
4. They recently changed the parking paradigm so now you have to collect a ticket and pay for parking at admission, which is truly the DUMBEST THING EVER. Until they change it back, park in the upper lot and as close to the rides as possible. This is important.
5. Dress said children in sturdy, comfy shoes that will not fall off their feet. See gondolas, roller coaster, running, frog pond, and any other number of fun things where shoes go missing.
6. Do not, under any circumstances, go to Tuskers, the restaurant. Not only is it crazy overpriced, it also takes exactly one elephant's life span to get your food. Unfortunately, they have excellent french fries, so you will be tempted. See #2.
7. Best exhibits: the California Experience (new high speed gondola up to the highest point of the zoo), the lions (best view of those guys from the original gondola ride near the train tracks), the lower Children's playground and frog pond/alligator exhibit, and the amphibian and reptile house. We also love the bat house but that's not for everyone!
8. Best rides: the train, of course, but the line is long so be prepared to wait and have some fun riddle or something for the kiddos to do whilst waiting, otherwise you're just in for a lot of swinging from the corral railings. The carousel is well done and the tiger roller coaster is scary-fun, in a mostly good way. The littlest ones will like the car "driving" ride and the carousel, the Jeep ride and perhaps the airplanes. Tickets for rides are the best deal at $24 for 16 booklet. Otherwise they're $1.75 each.
9. End your day at the rides, bribe everyone with a cotton candy or ice cream to get them to leave, and then voila! You're right near your car and the exit!
10. Become a member. We kvetch, but the money is immediately made up in just one family outing, and it goes to a really good cause!

If they would just revamp the management, put a little more pep in everyone's step, and sweep and paint the place so it doesn't look so shabby and run down, then we'd be in business. Dare I say we might even get 4 or more stars.< /review>
< Rate>
3<//Rate>
< response>

< review>
Visited with my then 6 year old son mid-week, on a day threatening rain so we had the place pretty much to ourselves.

Sat on a bench for a while watching a chimpanzee idle his way through a Seventeen magazine, glancing up every page or two to see what his (her) mates were up to.

Hard to convey how electrifying it was to experience the presence of this animal that seemed just a few notches away from humanity.  Stayed with me for days.<//review>

< text>
I went to the Oakland zoo last Friday with my daughter‚Äôs class for a field trip. The trip was well planned out. At the zoo they have classrooms for all of the guided tours. Our teacher/tour guide was supper friendly and had lots of information to give out.

This is my first time going to the zoo and I was surprised to see how nice the zoo was.  It is a large zoo and the animals looked happy for the most part. The best part of the zoo was seeing all of the animals out and about. We saw the lions, elephants, giraffes and flamingos just to name a few. (Going early is probably the best time).

After the tour the kids were able to go back to the classroom and have lunch. They also have a nice courtyard for the kids to eat at. The day we went it had just rained, so we were not able to enjoy the outside area.
Next to classroom was a whole area set up for the kids to run and play. I loved how you could explore and find new areas of the zoo. The kids had a great time seeing the bug exhibit and crocodiles. I also liked that the exhibits were scattered throughout the park and exploring with the kids was so much fun.

My group had time to pet the animals which was a nice touch. I wish I had more time to explore the zoo, but the bus was ready to pick us up and go back to school.< /text>

< Review>
Wonderful zoo in the rather challenged city of Oakland.  Animals appear well cared-for, and the happy families of all races and ethnicities are a lesson for xenophobes.  Beautiful new gondola lift to a counter restaurant on the hilltop, where the food is better than in most such places.  Love it.<//Review>

Pretty decent as zoos go.  Not too big,  on a hilly slope that is a bit of a workout pushing strollers on a hot day!.  The new gondola looks cool, takes you to top of the zoo, but the line was too long for us that day.  Giraffe, and primate exhibits I liked best.  Petting zoo also,  looked overrun with kids, animals mostly goats.  Cafes at the top.  Train ride is teriffic and there is a small midway for kids.  $24 adults free under 2yrs and I think around $18? for 7yr old.</Text>

0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa< /Gmap_id>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
I think this zoo is just the right size; it's not exhaustingly enormous, but it's not too small either, so my friend and I were able to see almost all the exhibits within 2.5 hrs. The staff members were very friendly and helpful, so we were able to ask questions and learn a lot about the animals we saw. If anything, I highly recommend taking the gondola up to the northmost exhibit. There's a playground for kids, lots of endemic species of animals to see up close, and an outlook point with an excellent view of the bay and San Fransisco! The parking lot fills up pretty quickly, so I suggest arriving at open.< /Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating></record></dataset><record>
<Resp>None<//Resp><Name>Eyal Cimet< /Name>< review>
Excellent zoo and educational experience for the whole family. The zoo is well designed (for actual walking and not vehicles like other zoos) and the exhibits are very well thought out. Went with a 3 and 5 year old and we had to leave when the zoo closed. Staff was very friendly and professional even when crowded. Recommend bringing your own food since the cafes get really crowded during meal times. Both cable cars are a must in my opinion, the other stuff (train, carousel, etc) is more of a money trap :)

Plenty to do, will definitely go back. Highly recommended!<//review>

<response>{'time': 1569601091031, 'text': 'Alwayd helpful'}< /response><Name>Harold Johnson</Name></record>
</dataset><record>
<response>None</response><Pics>None<//Pics>< Text>
I've lived in the Bay Area since 1990. I just visited the Oakland Zoo for the first time this year. My friends and I arrived before the gates opened and joined a line. It's a little, ok a lot, crazy at the gates before they open. Lots of confusion, coupled with excitement. Screaming kids, yelling parents, the usual. Once the gates open, it's a free for all. Everyone is pushing and running. I'm convinced the adults misbehave more than adults.
Once inside, we made our way to the new gondolas. We were literally the first ones there and ended up waiting a few more minutes for the attraction to open. No worries.
The gondolas were comfortable and clean. The boarding and exiting process were seamless. (even for a wheelchair in my party)
The views from the gondolas are phenomenal. The higher you go, the more of the Bay Area you see. The gentle breeze was a welcomed bonus.
The food court was a pleasant surprise. Personally, I don't think the prices were too high. The food was actually delicious. Each of us got something different and none of us were disappointed.
We enjoyed all of the animals and exhibits. I'm glad we went early. The park gets really crowded. It really warms up too. I thought I was going to pass out while visiting the camels. Can't wait to go back now that the new exhibits are open.<//Text>

<Date>1518928688445</Date><rating>5< /rating>< Text>
Oakland zoo is good, my daughter enjoyed the day at zoo. There is lots of parking space , if you are late then you will need to park the vehicle uphill and walk back quite a distance. $7 for stroller rental, in case if you have not carried the stroller. Some of the rides like train ride , and few others are paid ones. Gondola ride is included in the ticket. Cotton candy , popcorn is $4 a pack. Restrooms are clean and neatly maintained. You need 4-5 hours to cover the entire zoo.<//Text>

I really enjoy talking my young children to this zoo. They haveba good range of big animals and some interesting less common exhibits, like bats. They also have a petting zoo for children.

<Text>Awesome!!!! One of the BEST zoos I've ever been too! The first, in fact. I used to live in Oakland and conveniently close to the zoo. Even now in Danville, a town Contra Costa County, but along the border of Alameda County, I still live close, for it is on the other side of San Ramon. I've always loved that zoo ever since I was little and I still love it now. Eleven years ago, I also attended a zoo camp program and LOVED IT!!!!

I strongly recommended this zoo to everyone - especially those that live in the East Bay. I also recommend this zoo to scientists, like myself, those that want the access to animals they don't usually get to encounter, those that love nature and being outdoors, and all Lion King fans, such as me!!

Every time I've been to the Oakland Zoo, the place has also reminded me of the animal/nature films I grew up with such as Dumbo, The Jungle Book, and of course, The Lion King. I've been there many times with friends and I'm strongly hoping to get a job there someday.

I've had so much experience with the Oakland Zoo and have loved it! Everyone there is treated like friends and family. It is a perfect place for others to spend time at and socialize, and also to hold events.

If you need time to spend with lions, tigers, elephants, bears or other animals you don't get to be with everyday, come to the Oakland Zoo and see how awesome that zoo really is!< /Text><Pics>None</Pics>< response>
{'time': 1599151439106, 'text': "Thank you so much for the nice review Peter. We're happy you love to visit so much."}</response>

<review>Born an raised in Oakland, always had a good time. We got the membership for our family, why take the kids to the park when you can go to the zoo any day! The animals look healthy, it's well kept, and plenty to see. They are expanding the zoo to add a few more animals which is great. The lift to the cafe up top is free, also has a great view of Oakland. I've been taking my daughter here since she was born and she pretty much memorized the entire park. Shes never bored of it. Theres always something new to learn or talk about. Fun for the entire family. If you dont enjoy walking especially uphill, then that's a shame. It's great exercise for the kids and for yourself. The amusement park on the side of the zoo is fun for the kids too, the only ride I didn't like is the tiger roller coaster. I took my daughter on it recently for the first time. Seemed pretty dangerous because it didn't really secure her in place. If I wasn't in the ride with her, holding her head, she definitely would have hurt herself. Possibly banging her head into the ride. Other than that the other rides are safe and in great order.< /review><Name>adam pham<//Name><Rating>5</Rating><time>1531120880623< /time><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO9Fmgzc522-9vSH_Odj47NwMGxehB1dMP104Gx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures>< GmapID>

103520359097052774538</user>
< gmap_id>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa<//gmap_id>
< Review>
It was a beautiful day for the zoo. When I arrived with my family to spend the day with the kids we entered the park around 11 am. We got directed to the farthest part of the park. We didn't get any options of where to park which might be harder for families who have strollers or have family memebers who are disabled. Walking on grass isn't easy for you to push your stroller. Once coming on from the bottom entrance we loved every spot from the insects to tortoises. The kids love exploring the park and seeing these animals through very safe displays. We didn't have the chance ro ride the train but it looked really fun if we have another chance down the road.the newest part of the park, which you have to take the newest gondola, was great! The gondola goes up high and smoothly as long as you stay seated and don't move a lot. Each gondola can hold up to 6 adults which is great for families who have kids and many adults. Once to the top the bison were nice. The main attraction were the grizzly bears which you could see them from all angles and they could have privacy, have a swim to cool off and enjoy a simple swim. The cages up here were well thought out and they seem tranquil.when we got back down we went through the safari section of the park. When we got to the lion exhibit we could not see them but we definitely could hear them. When we got to elephant part one of the elephants seems depressed but I don't know why. I hope the people at the zoo see this and help it. At the very end we walked the whole park and left 40 minutes after closing time but we lived the park. If you go on a beautiful sunny day you can see the north part of the bay easily as we did. Would I go back? Yep it was definitely a great experience and recommend this to all families! !! üòÅüòÜüòä< /Review>

< Review>
pretty good. takes 2-3 hrs to see everything if you really take your time, and 1hr if you zoom through.  we planned going near end of day to get the best chance to see the nocturnal animals like the big cats, and it worked out perfectly.  could not see them around at 2:30PM, but by 5PM they came out and it was nice (esp., hyena, tigers, lions.  they don't kick you out until 5:30PM.  the tram over the africa section is not worth it unless you want to see the awesome west bay vista views or if you could not see the big cats b/c they hide where the tram can see them.</Review>

<UserId.>112956867367107188969</UserId.><user_name>Heather Young</user_name><time>1489773225400</time><rate>4< /rate>< review>
What a fun place! I'm used to going to the San Diego zoo (which is one of the best in the world!), so I honestly went not expecting much. I'm happy to report that the Oakland zoo was actually fairly big, hosting elephants, giraffes, lions, and much, much more. You won't find any Arctic animals or pandas like in San Diego, but I'd say for the price it's a decent zoo. My two year old and I spent a good 5 hours there, but it could have been longer if we'd bought lunch or gone on the kid rides. I have to say my only complaint is the price of the rides--we didn't go on them because they were exorbitant!<//review>

<Date>1564394692592</Date><gmap_id>0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</gmap_id><pictures>None</pictures><review>This zoo keeps getting better and better, and it's in a beautiful setting in the oakland hills.
Zoo personnel around the grounds are available for questions about the animals.
This is one of very few zoos that has African elephants instead of Asian.  It takes 20 keepers to care for the 4 elephants.
You can visit bars, bugs, reptiles and alligators in the children's zoo and of course , owt the goats.
Newer native animal section at the top of the hill.  Gondolas take you up to the top of the hill to a wheelchair accessible walkway thru native California animal enclosures including Grizzlies, condors, mountain lions and gray wolves.
Get to the zoo when it opens, there's a lot to see and parking fills up fast< /review></record>

< user_name>
B Martin<//user_name>
<date>1539655889242</date><Rating>4<//Rating>< review>
Well worth a visit. However, call in advance if you are planning to see the elephants being fed. When we visited with our grandchild, the elephant exhibit was closed with heavy equipment sitting around. However, all the large animals are being fed in the morning shortly after opening. It was interesting watching the giraffe and camels munching on branches that seemed inedible. We especially enjoyed the jaguar, mountain lion, and grizzly bear exhibits (reached by gondola). The black bear exhibit was great. We had a front row seat watching a large bear floating on its back with it's paws up out of the water only three or four feet away through a glass partition.</review>

< text>
For my list, I've created a bucket list of places to go. And they've been to all the zoos beside Oakland zoo. In December, one of my friends went to the Oakland Zoo with her 2 year old and family. She cognizant that Oakland zoo is not huge and not that many animals to see.  Although her reviews were stuck in my heard, I still sought to see for myself.
Entrance- At the zoo parking entrance, you have to pay $10. There were signs posted on the windows of the entrance, credit card system temporarily down and cash accepted. I pretended as if we didn't read the instruction and gave my credit card. They guy said you don't have cash. I replied, no. Then he swiped my card. I guess to speed up at the entrance, they posted those signs.

We purchased the tickets at the  zoo entrance and I kept saying to myself that should have purchased the groupon deal. It was expensive, $19 per adult without tax and for 2 year and up they charge.  I think best time to come to the zoo is in the morning. We reached the zoo at 10.30am and the parking lot was almost full. At the entrance, make sure to grab the map so you don't miss out anything. Once you enter the zoo you'll see the gift shop on your right and the flamingos directly in front of you. Near the gift shop are the restrooms and on the left is the restaurant where we ate.  The gift shop is small but remarkable,  great educational toys, t-shirts, hats, sunblock, puzzles and etc.

Outside the zoo is the Outback Express Adventure Train.  They have a train ride for adults and children that go around the zoo. Every time my daughter see the train, we have to ride. And she loved it. Our conductor did not give much information.
After paying the zoo entrance, we paid additional for the train ride. I felt everything was adding up very fast.

Wear comfortable shoes because there are steep hills in different portions of the zoo.
For the sky ride, you have to pay $ 3per person. I have 9 months old and they charged $3 for the baby. You can see most of the animals through the sky ride and it was totally worth it. I loved the newly opened Gondola ride. It had a beautiful view of the bay area. We saw elephants, giraffes, zebra, turtle, lemur, lion, buffalo, tiger and etc.

Overall, this was a great zoo and I would definitely come back when the new area is opened.</text>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>

< rating>
5< /rating>
<Review>We love Oakland Zoo.  They work hard to provide human enclosures and treatment for the animals.  Some other posters mentioned trash in the enclosures.  They give the animals different things for enrichment.  What looks like trash is actually for the benefits of the animals to keep them stimulated and healthy.

They also have a fun amusement area outside of the zoo.  You can access those rides without paying for entrance.  My son loves the train.  It takes you to the Australian Outback which has emus, wallaroos and a fantastic view of the bay.

Their annual Walk in the Wild fundraising event is awesome.  We went last year and can't wait to go this year.  It's so much fun.</Review>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

< Review>
I liked seeing the giraffes! It was not hard for me to walk around the hills and you could see all the animals that were out. The hyenas looked well groomed although they were quiet. I did not have anything to eat here but you are not forced to eat the cafe food as there are benches and grassy areas for you to have a picnic with your own food from home if you want. But it is a bit expensive as you have to pay about $40 for two adults, then extra for rides inside the park, plus $10 parking, and it is not as interactive or with such engaging staff as somewhere like Seaworld.</Review>

Bryan Meyer</user_name>
< date>
1472549222773</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
Phenomenal Zoo - best one in the Bay Area (or so I've heard).  Seeing the Giraffes is amazing - closest you'll ever get in a zoo in the US.  They have lions, tigers and bears (okay maybe not bears - I forget) oh my.

Good variety of animals - also have some nice kid play areas and structures.  There's a good little creek/pond and hill area where you can walk through.  Their restaurant and food options are meh - so be prepared.

You can get discounts on tickets if you're a member of other parks such as Happy Hollow Children's Park and Zoo of San Jose.</Text>

< review>
We do a zoo trip every fathers day with some friends and were all very surprised by Oakland zoo. The park is clean, the enclosures are large. There are some steep walking paths as the park is situated in hills east if the highway. There is a gondola ride up to a cafe and future expansion, a train ride, and children's carnival type rides.< /review>

Quite a lovely zoo. Well-maintained. Not a lot of concessions. I didn't have the overwhelming feeling of animals being oppressed like you get art some zoos. There's a petting area.

<review>The zoo is a pretty good size for an afternoon trip with kids. It takes about 3 hours to walk around the zoo to see all animals. Visitors are welcome to bring their own food to picnic there as well as have meals there is their various restaurants.
We got a chance to see many animals in action but it's a pity that the distance is too far for phone cameras.

There are a few things to note here though.
1. Kids need admission fee after 2. Unlike SF zoo, which offers kids free until they're 3.
2. Parking fee is $9 per car.
3. They do take 'passport' discount. =D
4. All the rides inside are extra. Sky ride is $3 per person and it's a around 20 minutes ride and you got a good view of the zoo. The play ground area is separated from the zoo and you can enter the area without zoo admission. Most rides there cost $1.5 and $3.

One thing about here is that I wish their staff can be more properly trained. The staff at entrance didn't even greet us and give us a map. Moreover, the staff at various exits didn't even bother to hold door for us even we have strollers, which is quite rude. I take one star off due to this.< /review>< pics>
None< /pics>

<Name>Rahim Khoja< /Name>< time>
1533150234679<//time>
<Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
Go early as the lines can get long.
If it's your first time, you'll need 3-4 hours to see the whole thing. Our 2 year old was done in about 3.

Almost all the animals were out and about but the bears were fun to watch. The zoo staff brought the 4 grizzlies close, to feed them fruits and play with them. The black bear cubs were having a blast amongst themselves, climbing on trees and jumping in the water. Don't miss taking the gondola ride to go see them at the California Trail section. Plus the view from the top is a bonus!!<//Review>

<review>This zoo has most of the animals you expect and hope to see at a zoo, the enclosures are decent sized, and the animals seem to be well cared for. The bathrooms are dated. The rides expensive, so we skip them. I wish there were more zoo staff around to talk to about the animals. And it's sometimes hard to see the animals due to the design of the pens.. which is probably best for the animals, but frustrating for children. Just be prepared for a hike, this zoo is on a hill and is a hike. I personally leave the stroller and take a carrier for my littles.</review><Pics>None<//Pics>< Resp>

< userid>
117587702328815101336</userid>
< name>
Duncan Crowley<//name>
< Date>
1532898413437<//Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
A few weeks ago I might have given this zoo only 3 stars because the lower part of the zoo is not extraordinary and it is quite crowded with loud young children. As you can imagine, this doesn't make me or the animals particularly happy. What redeemed all of those things for me was the new zoo expansion, known as the California trail. The area is accessible by a short gondola ride with the greatest view of the entire Bay. The gondola line was somewhat long when we rode up but was fast moving, and it was practically nonexistant when we rode down. The animals in this upper level were all CA animals, either historically (like the wolf and jaguar) or currently. The exhibits for all these animals were new and spacious, expanding the zoo's land area to nearly that of the great San Diego Zoo. I will say this zoo still pales in comparison to the one in San Diego, but is certainly the now best in the whole Bay area, and certainly more than worth the $20 entry fee. If you discounted this zoo before the expansion, I'd recommend giving it a second chance because the view on the California trail is more than worth the entry fee.< /Review>

< text>
Didn't realize Oakland had a zoo. It is a very nice zoo. The enclosures seem to be properly sized for the animals which is a nice change from most zoos. The 1 star off is because this zoo is expensive ($10 to enter the park the zoo is in, $22 for zoo admission). Lots of costly add ons (though not required). However, a new board walk section being built with a free gondola ride stands to be a great addition.

This is a good place to visit if you are looking for a different side of Oakland</text>

< text>
I had a bad experience at the Oakland Zoo today. My two sons 5 & 8 were looking forward to riding the plane ride that they always ride when they come to the zoo, but this time the ride operator told my son that he couldn't ride because he was too tall. I told her that I had just measured him next to their height requirement sign, and he was definitely under the max height limit which was 58 inches. The ride operator says "he is shorter than 58 inches, but we changed the height limit to 54 inches", I said if you changed it, u should of changed it on the signs, my son has been waiting excitedly in line to get on this ride. The ride operator acted like she didn't care that the sign said 58 inches, so I had the supervisor come down. The supervisor says, even if we go off the posted 58 inches sign, he is still taller, so I put him next to the sign & showed him my son was shorter than 58 inches, and the supervisor like no sorry he can't ride. He had the nerve to tell me that my son's hair counts as height (because my son has dreads that sit up on his head like a high top) so I put his hair in a ponytail to show he wasn't as tall, but he didn't care. I felt like they were intentionally trying to was upset me, yht supervisor saw he was wrong, but wasn't man enough to admit it, and apologize and let my son ride the ride. My son was so excited about going to the zoo, and he was enjoying himself, untill we got to the ride area, he was so disappointed. I will never go there again.</text>

< Review>
The size of the Oakland Zoo is perfect for toddlers and children under the age of 10.¬†Having visited both the San Diego Safari Park and the Omaha Zoo with open range enclosures, this small zoo managed to create some open space for the large animals like the giraffes, lions, tigers and elephants rather than enclose them entirely in a cage.¬†¬†¬†On a hot day, the shaded seats in the outdoor theatre can serve as a sitting area to rest or have lunch when there‚Äôs no show in progress.¬†¬†For those with children, the membership plans can be a good deal with free admission most days of the year.< /Review>

<user_id>107766957879264200934</user_id>< Review>
Don't get me wrong, it is fairly good zoo, but I felt like I wanted to see more. First things first. It is conveniently located just one block from highway and entrance is easily accessible regardless where you park. Admission price per adult is $17 which is not bad, but you actually have to pay more. Read until the end.

A few animals that I have seen are baboon, tigers, tortoise, elephants, camels, hyena, giraffes, wallaroo, otters, goats, etc. I have seen all these animals before and wanted to see more birds (only one parrot type, really?).

Some exhibits where closed and I would love to see anaconda, but I couldn't due to remodeling. Definitely there is lack of exotic insects.

The unexpected part was is the way of seeing wallaroo. It is only accessible with the small train and there is additional price of $3 per person for that. I thought that I am paying $17 to see animals.

Overall, it was OK experience, but I am not coming back. Work harder, Oakland Zoo</Review>

<Name>J L</Name><time>1537332562818<//time><rate>1</rate>< review>
Needs more exhibits and not enough animals in each exhibit. Also the wolf exhibit was inaccessable; you can only reach it via a gandola: if you don't mind waiting an hour and a half. Also, we were forced to park on the lawn area which the roads to get there were all muddy dirt, with huge potholes and very uneven ground. Only recommend a truck to park in the lawn area. In addition, there was only one cafe/resturant area to eat so imagine every person in the zoo going there to eat. It's ridiculous. Stay very away from this zoo. On the flip side the works we for the most part polite.< /review>

<UserId.>115619479914540105015</UserId.>< name>
Doris Schioberg</name>
< date>
1484364487593<//date>
<Rating>2<//Rating>< Review>
It's closer than the SF Zoo for people in the East Bay. That's about all that's really good about it. A lot of animals are hard to see for smaller kids, and often unnecessarily so, e.g., by painting a glass wall over. The staff is rarely helpful, most of the times they are more on the rude side. It's pricey and the rides are annoying. The kids always want to go to the rides instead of visiting the animals. It's my least favorite zoo but it's close enough to be convenient for a short morning entertainment, so I got a membership. After 11:30 AM it gets too full anyways.</Review>

<rate>4< /rate>< Review>
The zoo is a great place to spend a day with the kids.The new part of the zoo is fantastic.If you are afraid of heights you might not get to see the new part as the only way to it is by tram.The size of the zoo has doubled in size so there will be a lot of walking.The wolves are awsome to see.There is a male and a female.Just fyi the prices have gone up quite a bit also from tickets to get in to the food prices.On the weekends parking is horrible and traffic to get in even worse.All in all the Oakland Zoo is a fun place to go with or without kids.<//Review>

< review>
Very conflicted about this Zoo. On the one hand, they way the animals are kept rub me the wrong way, on the other hand how else do I expose my kids to animals other than raccoon and deer? While there with my kid the chimps were very agitated and didn't like the huge crowd watching them. The glass we were standing in front of broke when one chimp threw itself against the glass. We made the determination not to spend money here. And yet, I go back with my kid, because I have a kid, and they like zoos. Ignorance is bliss I suppose and you're never too old to be a hypocrite. Sigh.<//review>

< gmapID>
0x808f8f0df97f81df:0x201a254d74ff8aa</gmapID>
< review>
You would think by having the San Francisco Zoo, it would be enough, but we have another zoo across the bay, which in size, is not as enormous as San Francisco's but I think is just as enjoyable.

It offers residents in the Eastbay easy access for that "zoo fix" in most of us! ¬†I like the easy access from the freeway (Highway 580) and the large parking lot which is in front of the zoo.

With this zoo, you are walking up and down small hills to view the numerous animals but "my favorite part of the zoo has to be the sky-ride." ¬†I believe the San Diego Zoo is the only other zoo in California that is equipped with a "tram-like" ride over the zoo, but this one is a "ski-lift" type of ride, which I think is one of a kind.

The lift takes you over the lion's den and giraffe prairie and gives you a whole new perspective from above!

Another favorite attraction of mine is the meerkat exhibit where in the wild these animals live in large "clans" and to me is just entertaining to watch.</review>

< text>
Our son loved the Oakland Zoo, we got there when it opened and had a great 1/2 day (as that was all he could handle) we went back on Sunday to see the rest.  Loads of animals to see, you get really close and exhibits are close enough but a good spacing where you dont feel cramped.  The terrain is a little hilly though so I dont think I would bring grandparents as its a lot of up and downhill walking to certain parts.</text>

< Review>
A great place to take the kids to see a wide variety of animals.  This zoo has done a lot over the years to greatly increase the size of the animal enclosures.  You'll see African elephants, tigers, meerkats, zebras, lions, giraffes, camels, bison, a wide variety of birds, sun bears, baboons, monkeys, etc.  Included in the zoo is a children's zoo featuring repitles (including alligators), amphibians, various bugs & insects, fruit bats, lemurs, and more.  A separate train ride just outside the zoo gates will take you through an Outback with some Australian animals wander about.</Review>

< Text>
LOVED IT!! First time going to the Oakland Zoo. Kids had a blast seeing the animals & going on the rides. The main restaurant by the entrance was rather SLOW!! I waited 45 mins to 1 hour for our food. (unacceptable). Simple food like hot dogs, grilled cheese, nacho's took for ever!!
All in all it was an amazing quality time family day!!

Going back Dec 2- Jan 1 for Zoolights!!< /Text>

None</Pictures>
<review>We love the zoo! It focuses on safari and jungle animals and is currently missing california animals, but there is a california animal exhibit under construction. It's got lots of seating around the major habitats, like the elephants and monkeys. And it's got a great kids zoo. There are big animal statues to climb on all over and there is a petting zoo where the kids can pet/brush goats. The only downside is it's built on a hill, but that means you get a good workout! There is a small attached amusement park with rides you can pay for. There's also a train that goes around the zoo and a skylift that flies over it, though both of those cost money too. There are two train crossings, which my toddler loves! Its a great zoo and open all year round.< /review>< user_name>
Sarah Burnham</user_name>
